# Accessibility — Binding Directive

This is THE canonical accessibility rule file for this project. Read it before every code-generation task. Nothing ships without meeting these invariants.

## Core Principle

**Accessibility is the DEFAULT.** Non-accessible output requires an EXPLICIT, JUSTIFIED opt-out — a prop literally named `unsafeDecorative` with a required `reason: string`. If you find yourself reaching for `unsafeDecorative`, STOP and ask the user first.

The components in `{{ld_component_path}}/` enforce the a11y invariants they can. The runtime scanner mounted in `{{app_entry}}` enforces the rest — it throws into the Vite dev overlay when any commonly-slipped defect lands in the DOM. If you run `npm run dev` and see a full-screen error starting with `LD a11y:` or `A11Y:`, you introduced an a11y regression — fix it, don't suppress it.

### How to discover violations without a browser

The scanner POSTs every violation set to `/__ld_a11y_report` on the Vite dev server. A dev-only plugin:

1. **Prints a red banner to `npm run dev` stdout** with numbered violations. If you started the dev server with `run_in_background=true`, check its output.
2. **Writes the latest report to `.ld-a11y-report.json`** at the project root. After exercising the app, run `cat .ld-a11y-report.json` to see the current violation set in JSON.
3. **Serves the live snapshot at** `GET http://localhost:<port>/__ld_a11y_report`. Use `curl` to check without opening a browser.

If the scanner never fires, the app may not have rendered — ensure you've loaded the page at least once (`curl http://localhost:<port>/` or open it in a browser / automation tool). The scanner runs inside the browser, so the page must be visited for violations to surface.

## Hard Rules

### Images and media

- MUST use `<Image src="…" alt="…">` from `{{ld_component_path}}/Image`. NEVER use raw `<img>` elements.
- `alt` MUST be a meaningful description of what the image conveys. Short. Concrete. No "image of", no filename, no placeholder.
- NEVER write `alt=""`, `alt="image"`, `alt="photo"`, or `alt="..."` — the runtime rejects these.
- If (and only if) the image is PURELY decorative (visual flourish that adds nothing a screen reader user needs), MUST pass `unsafeDecorative={{ reason: "<why>" }}`. Ask the user before using this.

```tsx
// CORRECT — meaningful alt
<Image src={photoUrl} alt="3-in-1 Blender with glass pitcher" />

// CORRECT — decorative only, with justification
<Image src={heroFlourish} unsafeDecorative={{ reason: "aesthetic hero pattern" }} />

// WRONG — raw <img>
<img src={photoUrl} alt="3-in-1 Blender" />

// WRONG — placeholder alt
<Image src={photoUrl} alt="..." />
<Image src={photoUrl} alt="" />
<Image src={photoUrl} alt="image" />
```

### Icons

- Icons that carry meaning (status, action type, affordance) MUST have `a11yLabel`.
- Icons next to a text label that already describes the action MUST pass `decorative` (the icon is then `aria-hidden`).
- NEVER leave a standalone icon without either `a11yLabel` or `decorative`.

```tsx
// CORRECT — labeled standalone status icon
<Icon name="Warning" a11yLabel="Error" />

// CORRECT — decorative icon next to a text label
<Button leading={<Icon name="Truck" decorative />}>Free shipping</Button>

// WRONG — standalone icon with no label and no decorative flag
<Icon name="Warning" />
```

### Interactive elements

- MUST use `Button`, `IconButton`, `LinkButton`, or `Link` for interactive elements.
- NEVER add `onClick` / `onKeyDown` / `role="button"` to a `<div>`, `<span>`, `<li>`, `<td>`, or any non-interactive element.
- NEVER build an icon-only button with `<button>` + icon — use `IconButton` (it requires `a11yLabel`).
- For a whole-card click target, wrap the card in an `<a href>` or a `<Button>` so ONE real interactive element receives the click. Do not wrap the card in `onClick`.
- **Visible selection state implies interactivity.** If an element shows it is "active", "selected", or "current" via a border, background, checkmark, or any other visual signal, it MUST be a real interactive element (`<button>`, `<a>`, `Button`, `IconButton`, etc.) with `aria-pressed` / `aria-current` / `aria-selected` and a keyboard handler. NEVER render a non-interactive `<div>` / `<span>` / `<li>` carrying selected-state styling — sighted users will (correctly) try to click it, and keyboard / screen-reader users will have no way to operate it. A common offender is a thumbnail strip on a PDP: each thumbnail with an "active" border MUST be a `<button aria-pressed>` with `onClick`, not a styled `<div role="img">`.

```tsx
// CORRECT — icon-only action
<IconButton a11yLabel="Add to favorites"><Icon name="Heart" decorative /></IconButton>

// CORRECT — entire card is a link
<a href={productUrl} aria-label={product.name}>
  <Card>{/* content */}</Card>
</a>

// WRONG — clickable div
<div onClick={handleClick}>…</div>

// WRONG — bare button with icon child, no label
<button><Icon name="Heart" /></button>
```

### Pages and landmarks

- Every page MUST be wrapped in `<Page title="…">` from `{{ld_component_path}}/Page`. It renders the skip link, the `<main>` landmark, and the single page `<h1>` for you.
- **Exactly ONE `<Page>` per app.** The page module that represents the active route owns the `<Page>` — `App.tsx` MUST NOT render its own `<Page>` around it. Two `<Page>` wrappers produce two `<main>` landmarks and two `<h1>` elements; the runtime a11y scanner will throw and assistive tech navigation breaks.
- There MUST be exactly ONE `<h1>` per page. `<Page>` owns it. If you want a different VISIBLE page heading (e.g., rendered by a `Header` pattern or a hero), pass `titleVisuallyHidden` to `<Page>` and render your visible heading as an `<h2>`.
- NEVER write `<main>`, `<h1>`, or a skip link by hand — use `<Page>`. Writing them manually competes with the Page wrapper and the runtime scanner will throw.
- Section headings MUST start at `<h2>` (the level immediately below the Page h1) and step by one. NEVER skip heading levels (h2 → h4). Use `<Heading as="h2">` / `<Heading as="h3">` from the Text module.

```tsx
// CORRECT
<Page title="Cart">
  <section aria-labelledby="order-summary-heading">
    <Heading as="h2" id="order-summary-heading">Order summary</Heading>
    …
  </section>
  <section aria-labelledby="delivery-heading">
    <Heading as="h2" id="delivery-heading">Delivery</Heading>
    …
  </section>
</Page>

// WRONG — hand-rolled landmark + heading
<main>
  <h1>Cart</h1>
  <div><h2>Order summary</h2>…</div>
</main>

// WRONG — heading level skip
<Page title="Cart">
  <Heading as="h4">Order summary</Heading>  {/* skipped h2 and h3 */}
</Page>

// WRONG — double Page wrapper (two <main>, two <h1>)
// App.tsx
<Page title="My App">
  <CartPage />          {/* CartPage already renders its own <Page> inside */}
</Page>

// CORRECT — App.tsx renders the page module directly; the page module owns Page
// App.tsx
<A11yAnnouncementProvider>
  <CartPage />
</A11yAnnouncementProvider>
// CartPage.tsx
<Page title="Cart">…</Page>
```

### Forms

- MUST use Living Design form components (`TextField`, `TextArea`, `Select`, `DateField`, `Checkbox`, `Radio`) for every input. They wire `label ↔ input`, `aria-describedby ↔ helperText`, and `aria-invalid ↔ error` automatically.
- MUST render error text through the component's `error` prop — NEVER as a sibling `<div>` near the input. A sibling error is visually-only and has no `aria-describedby` wiring.
- MUST render helper/description text through `helperText` — NEVER as a sibling paragraph.
- MUST group related radios/checkboxes with `FormGroup` so they share a label.
- MUST NOT render a visual "required" asterisk without the native `required` attribute — screen readers need both.

```tsx
// CORRECT — label, helper, error all tied together by the component
<TextField
  label="Email"
  value={email}
  onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
  helperText="We'll only use this for order updates."
  error={touched && !valid ? 'Enter a valid email' : undefined}
  required
/>

// WRONG — error as a loose sibling
<TextField label="Email" value={email} onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
{touched && !valid && <div style={{color: 'red'}}>Enter a valid email</div>}

// WRONG — required asterisk rendered without the native required attribute
<TextField label="Email *" value={email} onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
```

### Color and meaning

- NEVER convey state or meaning through color alone. Pair color with text, an icon with a label, or a visible pattern.
- Status dots, badges, chart series, form validation — all need a non-color signal.

```tsx
// CORRECT — color + labeled icon + text
<Tag color="negative" leading={<Icon name="Warning" decorative />}>Error</Tag>

// WRONG — bare red dot means "error" only by color
<span style={{ background: 'red', width: 8, height: 8, borderRadius: 4 }} />
```

### Dynamic content and live regions

- MUST announce async updates to assistive tech using `useAnnounce()` from `{{ld_component_path}}/A11yAnnouncement`:
  - `announce.polite("3 results found for 'blender'")` — filters, search result counts, non-urgent updates.
  - `announce.assertive("Your session will expire in 1 minute")` — urgent only. Use sparingly.
- Store-connected cart bindings announce add/remove automatically — don't double-announce.
- `<Alert>` added dynamically to the DOM MUST mount inside a container present on page load with `role="alert"` or `aria-live="polite"`. The `A11yAnnouncementProvider` mounted in `{{app_entry}}` already provides global live regions — prefer `useAnnounce()` over building your own.

```tsx
// CORRECT — announce filter results
import { useAnnounce } from "{{ld_component_path}}/A11yAnnouncement";
const announce = useAnnounce();
useEffect(() => { announce.polite(`${results.length} results for "${query}"`); }, [results, query]);

// WRONG — assume re-rendering the list is enough
// Screen readers do not see layout changes; they see DOM announcements.
```

### Overlays and focus

- `Modal`, `Panel`, `BottomSheet`: the trigger element MUST receive focus back on close. The easy way is to trigger them from a `Button` — the wrappers track focus return automatically.
- NEVER build a modal/drawer with a bare `<div style={{position: 'fixed'}}>`. It has no focus trap, no Esc key, no scroll lock, no focus return. Use the Living Design overlay components.
- A dialog that mounts without focus inside it is a defect. `Modal`/`Panel`/`BottomSheet` handle this; custom overlays don't.

### Keyboard

- Every pointer interaction MUST work by keyboard. If you write `onClick`, you almost always need a real `<button>` underneath.
- MUST preserve tab order. NEVER use `tabIndex > 0`. Use `0` or `-1` only.
- For drag-and-drop, carousels, drawers: use the Living Design components — they include keyboard support. Custom rolled ones almost certainly do not.

### Single-select choice groups

A row of pills / tabs / toggles where ONE option is selected at a time is a "radio group" pattern in ARIA terms. It MUST behave as a single keyboard stop — Tab enters the group, arrow keys move between options, Tab exits. Four tab stops for four pills is a defect.

- For "one of many" pill-style selectors (category toggles, view modes, filter-style single-select), MUST use `<SegmentedControl>` from `{{ld_component_path}}/SegmentedControl`. It implements roving tabindex + arrow/Home/End keyboard navigation.
- For switching between top-level page views, MUST use `<TabNavigation>` + `<TabNavigationItem>`.
- For single-select inside a form, MUST use `<Radio>` inside `<FormGroup>` (radios share a `name`; the browser handles keyboard nav).
- NEVER use `<ChipGroup>` + `<Chip selected>` for exclusive single-select. `<ChipGroup>`/`<Chip>` renders each chip as an independent `<button aria-pressed>` — that's the MULTI-select filter pattern where each chip toggles on/off independently of the others. Using it for "one of many" creates N tab stops and no arrow-key navigation.
- Any custom single-select group MUST implement the radiogroup keyboard contract: one tab stop (roving tabindex — exactly one child has `tabindex=0`, rest `-1`), Left/Up previous, Right/Down next, Home first, End last, Space/Enter activate. If you cannot implement this, use `<SegmentedControl>` instead.

The runtime scanner enforces this. It will throw `Single-select button group without keyboard-group semantics: …` when it sees 2+ sibling toggle buttons with one active outside a `role="radiogroup"` / `role="tablist"` wrapper, and `<role> … missing roving tabindex` when a `radiogroup`/`tablist`/`toolbar` has more than one item with `tabindex=0`. Fix, don't suppress.

```tsx
// CORRECT — SegmentedControl for one-of-many category toggle
<SegmentedControl
  aria-label="Meal category"
  value={category}
  onChange={setCategory}
  items={CATEGORIES.map((c) => ({
    value: c.label,
    label: c.label,
    icon: <Icon name={c.iconName} decorative />,
  }))}
/>

// CORRECT — ChipGroup for MULTI-select filter chips (each toggles independently)
<ChipGroup>
  {FILTERS.map((f) => (
    <Chip key={f.id} selected={active.has(f.id)} onClick={() => toggle(f.id)}>
      {f.label}
    </Chip>
  ))}
</ChipGroup>

// WRONG — ChipGroup used for EXCLUSIVE single-select
<ChipGroup>
  {CATEGORIES.map((c, i) => (
    <Chip key={c.label} selected={i === active} onClick={() => setActive(i)}>
      {c.label}
    </Chip>
  ))}
</ChipGroup>
```

### Focus indicators

- NEVER use `outline: none` / `outline: 0` on interactive elements without a replacement `:focus-visible` indicator. Keyboard users must be able to see where focus is.
- If you must suppress the default outline (usually because you're styling `:focus-visible` on a parent wrapper), pair it with an explicit `:focus-visible` rule on the same element:

```css
/* CORRECT */
.my-button { outline: none; }
.my-button:focus-visible { outline: 2px solid var(--ld-semantic-color-content-brand-default); outline-offset: 2px; }

/* WRONG — keyboard users cannot see focus */
.my-button { outline: none; }
```

### Motion and timing

- The project ships a global `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` guard that neutralizes all animations and transitions. DO NOT override or remove it. NEVER write CSS that disables or fights this at the component level.
- Auto-dismissing content (snackbars, toasts, banners with timers) MUST also be dismissable manually (close button) AND give the user enough time to read (WCAG 2.2.1). The default Snackbar/`useSnackbar` pattern handles this — use it.
- NEVER auto-advance carousels without a visible pause control. Prefer the default LD `Carousel` which does not auto-play by default.

### Overlays — Escape + scrim

- Overlays (`Modal`, `Panel`, `BottomSheet`) MUST close on Escape. The LD components do this automatically — don't intercept the Escape key.
- Click-outside (scrim click) is a convenience ONLY, not a substitute for Escape. Every overlay that supports scrim-close MUST also support Escape-close.
- Tooltips MUST be dismissable via Escape without moving focus (WCAG 1.4.13). The LD `Tooltip` handles this automatically.

### Loading and async content

- Containers that show `Skeleton` / `SkeletonText` / `Spinner` while loading MUST mark themselves `aria-busy="true"` during load and remove it when real content appears:

```tsx
// CORRECT
<section aria-busy={isLoading}>
  {isLoading ? <SkeletonText lines={3} /> : <Content />}
</section>
```

- For blocking async operations (form submit, route-level spinner), announce start/end via `useAnnounce().polite('Loading…')` and `.polite('Loaded')`.
- `Spinner` alone does not announce — pair it with text like "Loading" or an announcement.

### External links and new-window targets

- An `<a target="_blank">` MUST announce that it opens in a new window. Add visually-hidden context:

```tsx
import { VisuallyHidden } from "{{ld_component_path}}/VisuallyHidden";

<Link href="https://…" target="_blank">
  Terms of service<VisuallyHidden> (opens in new window)</VisuallyHidden>
</Link>
```

- NEVER silently open links in a new window without this announcement — it disorients screen reader and keyboard users.

### Dynamic banners and notifications

- A banner/alert that MOUNTS DYNAMICALLY (not present on page load) MUST have a live-region role so screen readers announce it:
  - Informational: `role="status"` with `aria-live="polite"`
  - Urgent / errors requiring immediate attention: `role="alert"` (equivalent to `aria-live="assertive"`)
- The LD `Alert`, `Banner`, `BasicBanner`, `OrderStatusBanner`, and `Snackbar` (via the `A11yAnnouncementProvider`) handle this. If you build a custom dynamic notification, include the role yourself — or better, use `useAnnounce()`.

## Intent → A11y Pattern Map

| Intent | Required pattern |
|---|---|
| Product image in card | `<Image src alt={product.name} />` — alt is the product name, NOT "product image" |
| Decorative hero illustration | `<Image src unsafeDecorative={{ reason: "…" }} />` |
| Icon-only button | `<IconButton a11yLabel="…">` |
| Icon next to text label | `<Icon name="…" decorative />` |
| Status badge meaning "error" | `<Tag color="negative" leading={<Icon name="Warning" decorative />}>Error</Tag>` |
| Whole-card click target | Real `<a href>` wrapping card content, NOT `<div onClick>` |
| Page shell | `<Page title="…">…content…</Page>` |
| Section heading | `<Heading as="h2">…</Heading>` — never skip heading levels |
| Search results count updates | `useAnnounce().polite(\`${n} results\`)` |
| Cart item added | Store binding auto-announces |
| Required email field | `<TextField label="Email" required value onChange error={…}>` |
| Form error beside field | `<TextField error="…">` (NEVER a sibling div) |
| Confirmation dialog | `<Modal title="…" isOpen onClose>` — focus returns to opener automatically |
| Side drawer from nav | `<Panel title="…" isOpen onClose>` |
| Empty search state | `<ContentMessage>` |
| Expand/collapse inline | `<Collapse isOpen>` — never a custom max-height toggle |
| Live status banner | `<Alert>` inside the global live-region provider (already mounted) |
| Pill-style category toggle (one of many) | `<SegmentedControl items value onChange aria-label>` — NEVER `<ChipGroup>`+`<Chip>` for exclusive single-select |
| Multi-select filter chips (each toggles independently) | `<ChipGroup>` + `<Chip selected>` — each chip is its own `aria-pressed` toggle |

## Opt-out Contract

The ONLY opt-out mechanism in this project is explicit, named, and justified:

- `unsafeDecorative={{ reason: string }}` — on `<Image>` when the image is purely decorative. Requires a non-empty reason.
- `decorative` (boolean) — on `<Icon>` when the icon sits next to a descriptive text label (this is routine and doesn't need a reason).

**Before using `unsafeDecorative` on an image, you MUST ask the user.** The runtime logs the reason string so every opt-out is visible in dev.

There is no other opt-out. There is no `a11yOff`, no `disableA11yCheck`, no global config flag. If a check is throwing, fix the violation.

## Pre-Response A11y Checklist

Before returning code, verify each:

- [ ] Is the page wrapped in `<Page title="…">` with exactly one `<h1>`?
- [ ] Do section headings step by one (h2 under Page, h3 under h2)? No skipped levels?
- [ ] Is every image written as `<Image>` with a meaningful `alt` (or justified `unsafeDecorative`)?
- [ ] Does every icon either have an `a11yLabel` OR `decorative` (never bare)?
- [ ] Is every interactive element a `Button` / `Link` / `IconButton` / `LinkButton` — no raw `onClick` on divs, spans, or other non-interactive elements?
- [ ] Do all form inputs use LD form components (`TextField`, `TextArea`, `Select`, etc.) with `label`, `error`, `helperText` props — no sibling-div error messages?
- [ ] Does state/status use text or a labeled icon — never color alone?
- [ ] Is dynamic content announced via `useAnnounce()` where a screen reader user would otherwise miss the update?
- [ ] Do overlays use `Modal`/`Panel`/`BottomSheet` — not custom `<div style={{position: 'fixed'}}>`?
- [ ] Did I use `unsafeDecorative` anywhere? If yes, did I ask the user first?
- [ ] If I wrote CSS with `outline: none`, did I pair it with a `:focus-visible` rule?
- [ ] Does any dynamic banner/notification I added have a live-region role (or use `useAnnounce()`)?
- [ ] Can every overlay I added be closed via Escape (built into `Modal`/`Panel`/`BottomSheet`)?
- [ ] For any "one-of-many" pill/tab/toggle UI, did I use `SegmentedControl` / `TabNavigation` / `Radio` — not `ChipGroup`+`Chip`?

If any box is unchecked, fix it before returning the code.
